title: Want To Buy:  I Need to Learn How to Reload (9mm)
location: London, Delaware, Dublin, etc, Columbus, Ohio
postcontent: I planned to start simple. I have a Lee Hand Press Kit, (300 BLK casings) Correction: 9mm, (Winchester 296 Powder) Correction: Alliant Unique and Hodgdon Tite Wad, (WSR primers) Correction: CCI Small Pistol Primers, and (168 grain HPBT projectiles) 90 Grain JHP, 115 Grain JHP and 115 Grain Ball. I have copious experience reloading 12 gauge for my two sons who shot trap until recently (one year, we reloaded 5000 rounds and STILL had to buy practice ammoI need someone who has done some reloading who can teach me the process so that I can transition to using the single stage press I have at home, then move up to the Hornady AP kit I have waiting, when my skill level allows me to crank out serious volume.  The end goal is to spend next Winter loading ammo, then not have to buy ANY ammo in 2018. I know. Everybody tries to do this, but they end up buying SOME ammo in the end.  If I have to buy SOME ammo, it's it's an improvement over buying all of it.//MAIN EDIT BEGINS:IMPORTANT:After several people told me that I should do this, I have changed my initial goal from 300 BLK to 9mm Para.  I have CCI 500 Small Pistol Primers1lb Unique1lb Tite Wad500 pieces of unpolished brass (un-decapped)Above are the items I have in my office and can lay eyes on.9mm Die (I think I know where it is.  If I can't find it, I will just buy another. It's not as if I can do without them.)EDIT ENDS//I can buy ammo for anywhere as $0.66 to $1.25Reloading costs would be approximately$0.28(avg projectile cost), a max of $0.50 in powder and, $0.04 for a primer.  The cases can be made from Lake City 5.56mm GI brass, which is almost free.  Ready Made 300 BLK, on the other hand, is $0.79. for a total of  $1.61 MAXIMUM.  More realistically, it will be made from reclaimed Lake City 5.56mm or 300 BLK cases that can be used several times for $0.82 for whichever bullet weight, shape, design and accuracy optimized for the rifles my son and I have in this caliber.  I am willing to pay you for your time in cash, powder, ready-to-load lead shot or you can keep a portion of the ammunition we load in the process of my learning to reload.  I am sure we can come to an agreement for your compensation.Eventually, I am going to have to learn to reload5.56mm257 Weatherby30/30308 Winchester300 WeatherbyIf I buy the case, it will make things less financially attractive, up front, but38 Special357 Magnum44 Remington Magnum (for pistol & carbine)9mm (for pistol & carbine)380acp45acp45/70 Government for Old Trapdoor actions and Modern Lever ActionsI think this is a complete list of calibers.  I do not expect you to tutor me on them.  I just think 300 BLK is a good place to start.  Even though the BLK is not the simplest of the rounds (I think the 9mm or the 380 would be) it is also not as difficult as some of the others, such as one of the Weatherby cartridges.

I got into long range precision while I was in the Army and finally built my own rifle, this rifle.  It's only been shot twice and cleaned accordingly.  It's a Remington 700 .308 Short Action 1-10 Twist.  Beyond that I have to speculate that it's the model SPS Varmint but I can't be completely sure, I didn't keep the receipt because I never intended on selling it.  The Sightron scope was recently sent back to the factory and serviced because a turret got stuck and I didn't want to damage it - these scopes come with a LIFETIME warranty so it was super easy (also note that there are no ring marks on the scope.  Vortex scope rings are great).  
Here's everything that comes with the kit;    Remington 700 with factory stock, XLR Carbon Chassis installed, Vism dragbag (folds out into a shooting mat - very handy), Timney Trigger installed, Sightron Siii SS 6-24x50 FFP LR scope, 10 round magazine, Weaver Multi-slot base 20 MOA installed, Vortex Precision Matched Scope Rings installed, Bore Guide (from Mike Lucas), Dewey Bore Rod, Hope's no. 9 cleaning solutions and assorted brushes.  I can install the scope if you like to factory settings or if you prefer, I can leave the scope off if you have a preferred set of rings that you would rather use.  This Sightron scope has made for excellent glass and customer service.  I've also added a "fast lever" on the scope to be able to adjust the scope faster.  Any of these things are easily removable, even the factory stock.  Going back to a deer rifle platform is as easy as two or three screws. All together I paid over 3000 for everything that I'm selling for 2500 cash, buyer pays for background check.  Thank you for looking, please let me know if you have any questions! Mark* For some odd reason there was no selection for "308 Winchester", so I selected .308 Nato but this is indeed a 308 Winchester caliber rifle.

Brand New H&K VP9 For Sale.  Comes with 2 Magazines and changeable rear straps.
The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall/crisp break. Typically, striker fired guns have a pre-travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. With the VP9, you have a less than noticeable pre-travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break.
The VP9 uses HK’s ergonomic handgun grip design that includes three changeable backstraps and six side panels— accommodating all hand sizes. Molded finger grooves in the front of the pistol’s grip also instinctively position an operator’s hand for optimal shooting. Only HK handguns have such a customized grip.
